<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "inLanguage": "en",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Who is this written for?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Parents and caregivers. Unlike a standard natal report (which is written for the person whose chart it is), the Parenting Guide is written for YOU — the parent. Every section includes practical guidance: what to watch for, how to respond, and what kind of environment helps your child thrive. The language is clear, direct, and free of jargon."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How young can my child be?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Any age. The birth chart is calculated from the moment of birth, so the report works whether your child is a newborn or a teenager. The themes in a chart describe tendencies and patterns — they don't require the child to have demonstrated them yet. In fact, some parents find it most useful early on, when they're still figuring out their child's temperament."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is this like a natal report?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It uses the same birth chart data, but the analysis is completely different. A natal report (\"Your User Manual\") is a self-reflective tool for adults — it covers identity, career, relationships, and personal growth. The Parenting Guide focuses on what parents need to know: emotional needs, learning style, talents, and challenges. Different audience, different lens, different output."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<!-- Schema.org: BreadcrumbList -->

